ich render Seneca into verse with as close a correspondence, line for line, to the original as possible, and with special attention paid to meter and overall flow. In addition, each tragedy is prefaced by an original translator’s introduction offering reflections on the work’s context and meaning. Notes are provided for the reader unfamiliar with the culture and history of classical antiquity. Accordingly, The Complete Tragedies will be of use to a general audience and professionals alike, from the Latinless student to scholars and instructors of comparative literature, classics, philosophy, drama, and more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aDRAMA / General.2bisacsh  aAntigone.  aArgos.  aDeianeira.  aLycus.  aStoicism.  aThebes.  acannibalism.  adeification.  aexile.  amadness.1 aAsmis, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartsch, Shadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartsch, Shadi.1 aBraund, Susanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraund, Susanna.1 aKonstan, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonstan, David.1 aNussbaum, Martha C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeneca, Lucius Annaeus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226013749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226013749/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles